between your approach and
Piketty's and what you think

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:47.840
of Piketty and what Piketty
might think of you--

00:41:47.840 --> 00:41:50.220
or not you, but I mean the work.

00:41:50.220 --> 00:41:53.070
JOSEPH BLASI: Well, if you--
don't worry about that-- if you

00:41:53.070 --> 00:41:56.510
see the paperback,
Thomas Pikkety's opinion

00:41:56.510 --> 00:41:58.740
about the book is on the
top of the front cover,

00:41:58.740 --> 00:42:00.840
so I'll let him
speak for himself.

00:42:00.840 --> 00:42:04.770
We met in Paris last
February just before he

00:42:04.770 --> 00:42:07.950
came to the United States, but
I will comment on his work.

00:42:07.950 --> 00:42:12.290
First of all, I think that
Thomas Piketty's work has

00:42:12.290 --> 00:42:15.990
created a big focus on
wealth and income inequality

00:42:15.990 --> 00:42:19.920
like there has never been,
and despite the debate--

00:42:19.920 --> 00:42:22.340
and by the way I
think that he is

00:42:22.340 --> 00:42:26.780
on solid ground
with his results--

00:42:26.780 --> 00:42:28.290
the census, the
Congressional Budget

00:42:28.290 --> 00:42:33.400
Office, and many other
sources support his results

00:42:33.400 --> 00:42:35.350
for the United
States concentration

00:42:35.350 --> 00:42:36.790
of wealth and income inequality.

00:42:36.790 --> 00:42:39.410
As to his solution,
yes, his solution

00:42:39.410 --> 00:42:42.440
would be called a
redistribution because what

00:42:42.440 --> 00:42:46.820
he would like to do is
have high income tax taxes

00:42:46.820 --> 00:42:48.750
for the wealthy,
in the 60%, 70%,

00:42:48.750 --> 00:42:54.640
80% range plus a modest
tax on all wealth assets.

00:42:54.640 --> 00:42:58.620
So high tax on annual
income and a modest 1% to 2%

00:42:58.620 --> 00:43:01.250
tax on all wealth.

00:43:01.250 --> 00:43:05.460
The rich would have to file
a report on their wealth.

00:43:05.460 --> 00:43:07.250
I will make two comments.

00:43:07.250 --> 00:43:11.810
First of all, if one applied the
broad-based property ownership

00:43:11.810 --> 00:43:14.370
approach of the founders
of the American Revolution

00:43:14.370 --> 00:43:17.800
and some of the suggestions
that we're talking about one

00:43:17.800 --> 00:43:20.330
could address this
in a different way

00:43:20.330 --> 00:43:23.090
by broadening
property ownership.

00:43:23.090 --> 00:43:24.870
And I think the
stark choice that we

00:43:24.870 --> 00:43:30.060
have is between redistribution,
broad-based property ownership

00:43:30.060 --> 00:43:33.130
attempts that we're talking
about, and feudalism.

00:43:33.130 --> 00:43:33.750
Right?

00:43:33.750 --> 00:43:35.910
At the time of the
American Revolution,

00:43:35.910 --> 00:43:40.690
the British aristocracy
controlled 80% of all land

00:43:40.690 --> 00:43:43.830
in England and you can see
the numbers that I showed you,

00:43:43.830 --> 00:43:45.590
those are US government
numbers -- census,

00:43:45.590 --> 00:43:49.950
Congressional Budget Office--
we're approaching or surpassing

00:43:49.950 --> 00:43:50.450
that.

00:43:54.290 --> 00:43:58.190
James Madison and others of the
founders at the Constitutional

00:43:58.190 --> 00:44:02.050
Convention worried about
this, and for those

00:44:02.050 --> 00:44:05.170
who have spent their
time attacking Piketty

00:44:05.170 --> 00:44:11.940
I will say, go and read the
Constitutional Convention book

00:44:11.940 --> 00:44:15.120
and you will see that they
said if we can't continue

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:18.490
to maintain broad-based property
ownership there will be calls

00:44:18.490 --> 00:44:22.100
through redistribution in a
democratic system, the majority

00:44:22.100 --> 00:44:25.400
that will be disenfranchised
will vote for higher taxes.

00:44:25.400 --> 00:44:31.090
So I think that that's a
problem and probably we're

00:44:31.090 --> 00:44:35.720
going to see a lot more conflict
over this issue in the future,

00:44:35.720 --> 00:44:41.000
unless the Republican and the
Democratic Party, both of which

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:44.590
seem to be bereft of any
real ideas other than

00:44:44.590 --> 00:44:46.250
lies on this issue.

00:44:46.250 --> 00:44:46.750
Right?

00:44:46.750 --> 00:44:50.080
The Republicans want you think
that every few years then

00:44:50.080 --> 00:44:52.410
give you a $1500
tax cut and it's

00:44:52.410 --> 00:44:54.800
going to solve wealth
inequality and the Democrats

00:44:54.800 --> 00:44:57.940
want you to think that they
can give you the minimum wage

00:44:57.940 --> 00:45:01.390
and health care and it will
solve wealth inequality.

00:45:01.390 --> 00:45:04.170
Both are just stark, stark lies.

00:45:04.170 --> 00:45:07.070
If we don't deal with
broad-based property ownership,

00:45:07.070 --> 00:45:12.750
I think there will be calls
for greater taxes on wealth

00:45:12.750 --> 00:45:13.450
and income.

00:45:13.450 --> 00:45:18.410
Although these things will be
very, very hard to implement.

00:45:18.410 --> 00:45:20.775
OK.

00:45:20.775 --> 00:45:21.900
Did I answer your question?

00:45:25.520 --> 00:45:26.590
AUDIENCE: Sort of.

00:45:26.590 --> 00:45:27.298
JOSEPH BLASI: OK.

00:45:27.298 --> 00:45:28.365
Well, come back to me.

00:45:28.365 --> 00:45:32.640
AUDIENCE: Maybe if I could
just add a mechanical problem.

00:45:32.640 --> 00:45:39.510
If the top 20% already
have 86% how are you

00:45:39.510 --> 00:45:41.770
get it away from them?

00:45:41.770 --> 00:45:43.780
Without doing redistribution.

00:45:43.780 --> 00:45:49.470
JOSEPH BLASI: Well, the policies
we talk about in the book

00:45:49.470 --> 00:45:52.110
don't involve
redistribution, they

00:45:52.110 --> 00:45:56.170
involve broadening
ownership opportunities.

00:45:56.170 --> 00:45:59.930
And if there are more
people that have capital

00:45:59.930 --> 00:46:02.250
than that number will go down.

00:46:02.250 --> 00:46:05.550
If you have broader capital
ownership, so for example,

00:46:05.550 --> 00:46:09.570
let's imagine Google was
built on the internet.

00:46:09.570 --> 00:46:14.630
Let's imagine the next 20
technological breakthroughs.

00:46:14.630 --> 00:46:19.400
OK, let's imagine an
economy with robots.

00:46:19.400 --> 00:46:24.910
These items, these
capital resources, I think

00:46:24.910 --> 00:46:29.490
should be largely owned by these
citizen trust private market

00:46:29.490 --> 00:46:32.500
economy corporations
to pay dividends.

00:46:32.500 --> 00:46:35.620
If you can envision the roll
out of what we're talking about,

00:46:35.620 --> 00:46:38.820
you will see that the
capital income and capital

00:46:38.820 --> 00:46:41.150
gains going to the
top would go down.

00:46:41.150 --> 00:46:43.415
Not because their property
was taken but because,

00:46:43.415 --> 00:46:45.150
as the founders
talked about, there

00:46:45.150 --> 00:46:48.150
were broader opportunities
for acquisition of property

00:46:48.150 --> 00:46:49.720
to everyone else.

00:46:49.720 --> 00:46:53.270
However I do want to be
very clear about this.

00:46:53.270 --> 00:46:56.900
I do not think that simply
broadening ownership

00:46:56.900 --> 00:47:00.260
in workplaces through profit
sharing and employee equity

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:03.550
is enough, I think you have
to have things like the Alaska

00:47:03.550 --> 00:47:06.610
Permanent Corporation
in addition.

00:47:06.610 --> 00:47:08.700
But we owe it to our
political traditions

00:47:08.700 --> 00:47:11.380
to at least try these things.

00:47:11.380 --> 00:47:13.770
That's the best I
can answer right now.

00:47:13.770 --> 00:47:17.110
I'm happy to talk with
you more afterwards.

00:47:17.110 --> 00:47:18.421
Yes?

00:47:18.421 --> 00:47:19.962
AUDIENCE: You just
mentioned that you

00:47:19.962 --> 00:47:23.234
